Geometric Persistence and Subspace Control: A Unified Theory of Rare Signal Preservation, Flatness, and Alignment in Ultra-Large Models

Ouadi Maakoul

---

Abstract

We present a unified geometric theory explaining how ultra-large models—those operating in the regime $D \gg \text{eff}(P_{\text{data}})$, hypothesized to emerge near $10^{12}$–$10^{13}$ parameters for web-scale data—preserve, utilize, and ultimately control rare, logically coherent signals despite their vanishing frequency in training data. The theory demonstrates that learning, generalization, and alignment reduce to subspace dynamics in overparameterized systems. We establish three foundational results. First, we prove an asymptotic decoupling rate for the Fisher Information Matrix, showing that distinct logical manifolds become orthogonal at a rate $\mathcal{O}(\sqrt{\text{eff}(P_{\text{data}})}/\sqrt{D})$ under mild isotropic assumptions. Second, we show that the Fisher Information Matrix and the Hessian align in the dominant eigenspace, unifying decoupling and flatness as a single geometric phenomenon. Third, we prove that rare generative grammars $G$ form stable, low-curvature attractor manifolds $\mathcal{M}_G$ under Stochastic Gradient Descent, provided they offer marginal predictive utility $\delta > 0$ on the broader data distribution. We then extend the analysis to post-training alignment, demonstrating that geometric isolation in the pretraining metric does not guarantee robustness under arbitrary external optimization. We derive explicit stability conditions (A3–A5) and propose Projection-Corrected Alignment, a geometric control mechanism that restricts alignment updates to the orthogonal complement of high-utility subspaces. Finally, we articulate four concrete, falsifiable empirical predictions that distinguish our geometric theory from alternative accounts of scaling and alignment. The framework suggests a paradigm shift: alignment in ultra-large models is not a scalar loss minimization problem but a geometric control problem over a factorized representation space.

---

1. Introduction

The scaling of neural network parameter counts into the regime $D \sim 10^{12}$–$10^{13}$ has revealed emergent capabilities not present in smaller models, including the apparent retention and synthesis of niche, highly structured knowledge. A paradox arises: how can a model internalize the content of a document seen only a handful of times—such as an esoteric paper on Finite State Automata (FSA) or Measure-Theoretic Event Boundary Segmentation (MEBS)—when the training corpus is dominated by high-frequency, generic text? Traditional learning theory suggests such rare signals should be treated as noise and diluted.

We resolve this paradox by formalizing the transition from dilution to decoupling in the ultra-overparameterized regime. Using tools from information geometry, implicit regularization, and dynamical systems, we show that mathematically rigorous rare signals become attractor states in the loss landscape, preserved not by frequency but by their compression efficiency and predictive utility. It is important to distinguish between two notions of "rarity" that we employ throughout this work: (i) syntactic sparsity—the concrete document appears with vanishing empirical frequency; and (ii) semantic structure—the document is generated by a compressed generative grammar $G$ with low description length. Our theory concerns the latter: the grammar $G$ is what the model ultimately encodes and preserves; the specific document serves merely as a low-entropy attractor that reveals the existence of the underlying manifold.

We then address a critical follow-up question: what happens to these preserved structures during post-training alignment (e.g., RLHF, instruction tuning)? We prove that the geometric protection afforded by pretraining does not automatically extend to alignment updates, and we derive explicit conditions for stability. This leads to a prescriptive framework for geometric alignment, where gradient updates are constrained to preserve high-utility, low-curvature manifolds.

Core Thesis. This paper introduces a geometric theory of representation persistence and control in overparameterized systems. We show that learning, generalization, and alignment reduce to subspace dynamics in the regime $D \gg \text{eff}(P_{\text{data}})$. The threshold where this regime begins is hypothesized to lie in the range $D \sim 10^{12}$–$10^{13}$ for web-scale corpora, based on qualitative consistency with observed scaling phenomena; the precise transition point depends on the effective rank (entropy) of the data distribution and remains an empirical question to be validated.

