2. Geometric Foundations: The Decoupling Limit

Let $f_\theta: \mathcal{X} \to \mathcal{Y}$ be a model parameterized by $\theta \in \mathbb{R}^D$. The training objective is the expected loss under the data distribution $P_{\text{data}}$:
\mathcal{L}(\theta) = \mathbb{E}_{x \sim P_{\text{data}}} \left[ \ell(f_\theta(x), y) \right]

Definition 2.1 (Fisher Information Matrix).
The Fisher Information Matrix (FIM) $F(\theta)$ captures the local curvature of the KL-divergence in parameter space:
F(\theta) = \mathbb{E}_{x \sim P_{\text{data}}} \left[ \nabla_\theta \log p_\theta(y|x) \, \nabla_\theta \log p_\theta(y|x)^T \right]


where $p_\theta(y|x)$ is the model's predictive distribution.

Definition 2.2 (Effective Rank).
Let $\text{eff}(P_{\text{data}})$ denote the effective rank (participation ratio) of the data distribution, defined as $\text{eff}(P) = \frac{(\sum_i \lambda_i)^2}{\sum_i \lambda_i^2}$ where $\lambda_i$ are eigenvalues of the data covariance.

Definition 2.3 (Dilution Regime).
When $D \ll \text{eff}(P_{\text{data}})$, the FIM $F(\theta)$ is dense and low-rank. The gradient of a rare signal $x_{\text{rare}}$ (frequency $\epsilon \to 0$) lies almost entirely in the span of gradients from high-density samples. Consequently, its Natural Gradient update $\tilde{\nabla}_\theta \mathcal{L} = F(\theta)^{-1} \nabla_\theta \mathcal{L}$ fails to isolate the rare concept, causing destructive interference and dilution into the dominant mode.

Definition 2.4 (Decoupling Regime).
In the ultra-overparameterized limit $D \gg \text{eff}(P_{\text{data}})$ (hypothesized to emerge around $D \sim 10^{12}$–$10^{13}$ for web-scale corpora, depending on data entropy), the FIM $F(\theta)$ exhibits Block-Diagonal Dominance. Let $\mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{M}_i}$ denote the orthogonal projector onto the dominant eigenspace of $F(\theta)$ corresponding to a logically distinct concept (manifold) $\mathcal{M}_i$. Then for any two such concepts $i \neq j$:
\mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{M}_i} F(\theta) \mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{M}_j} \approx 0 \quad \text{and} \quad \text{Tr}\left( \Sigma_{\mathcal{M}_i} \Sigma_{\mathcal{M}_j} \right) \ll 1


where $\Sigma_{\mathcal{M}_i}$ is the covariance of parameters projected onto $\mathcal{M}_i$.

Lemma 2.5 (Asymptotic Decoupling Rate).
Assume that within the subspace spanned by the top eigenvectors of the data covariance, the parameter gradients are approximately isotropic and the parameter space is uniformly overparameterized relative to the effective rank. Then, under the ultra-overparameterized regime $D \gg \text{eff}(P_{\text{data}})$, for any two distinct logical manifolds $\mathcal{M}_i, \mathcal{M}_j$, the Frobenius norm of the off-diagonal FIM block satisfies:
\|\mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{M}_i} F(\theta) \mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{M}_j}\|_F = \mathcal{O}\left(\frac{\sqrt{\text{eff}(P_{\text{data}})}}{\sqrt{D}}\right)


Justification. In high dimensions, random subspace overlaps scale as $1/\sqrt{D}$ by concentration of measure. The effective rank controls the number of active data directions; the residual interference decays with the square root of parameter count relative to data complexity. This bound is a scaling heuristic derived from random-matrix intuition; its primary role is to motivate the FIM–Hessian analysis and the empirical predictions.

Proposition 2.6 (FIM–Hessian Alignment in Overparameterized Regime).
Assume the model is well-specified (i.e., the true data distribution lies within the model class), the parameters are near a local minimum of the loss, and the mini-batch gradient noise covariance is bounded in spectral norm by $\|H\|$. Then the Fisher Information Matrix $F(\theta)$ and the Hessian $H(\theta) = \nabla_\theta^2 \mathcal{L}(\theta)$ converge in the subspace spanned by high-eigenvalue directions:
\mathcal{P}_{\text{high}} F(\theta) \mathcal{P}_{\text{high}} \approx \mathcal{P}_{\text{high}} H(\theta) \mathcal{P}_{\text{high}}


where $\mathcal{P}_{\text{high}}$ projects onto the dominant eigenspace. Consequently, the decoupling of manifolds (a property of $F$) and the flatness of those manifolds (a property of $H$) are not separate effects—they are the same geometric phenomenon viewed through different lenses.

Consequence: The Natural Gradient update $\tilde{\nabla}_\theta \mathcal{L}$ for $x_{\text{rare}}$ is effectively orthogonal to the subspaces of common language. Rare signals cease to be noise; they become isolated degrees of freedom.

