11. Conclusion

We have presented a complete geometric theory of rare signal preservation in ultra-large models, spanning both pretraining dynamics and post-training alignment. The framework demonstrates that mathematically rigorous, low-frequency concepts survive not by chance but as attractor states in the loss landscape, stabilized by compression efficiency and marginal predictive utility. We quantified the decoupling rate of distinct logical manifolds as $\mathcal{O}(\sqrt{\text{eff}(P)}/\sqrt{D})$ and unified the phenomena of decoupling and flatness through the alignment of the Fisher Information Matrix and the Hessian.

We further showed that post-training alignment poses a distinct threat to these structures, requiring explicit geometric constraints to prevent subspace collapse or drift. The proposed Projection-Corrected Alignment offers a principled path toward retaining deep, niche knowledge while shaping model behavior. As models continue to scale, the ability to navigate and control their internal geometry will become as critical as optimizing scalar loss functions. The rare can remain inevitable—if we build the tools to preserve the spaces where logic lives.

