12. Empirical Predictions

To ensure the theory is falsifiable and empirically grounded, we articulate four concrete predictions that distinguish our geometric framework from alternative accounts of scaling and alignment.

Prediction 1: FIM Sparsity Transition.
As a function of the ratio $D / \text{eff}(P_{\text{data}})$, the off-diagonal Frobenius norm $\|\mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{M}_i} F(\theta) \mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{M}_j}\|_F$ should decay as $1/\sqrt{D}$ for $D \gg \text{eff}(P)$. In practice, the projectors $\mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{M}_i}$ can be estimated by performing PCA on concept-specific activation vectors (e.g., activations for prompts about "FSA" vs. "Control Theory"). The empirical Fisher (or Hessian) can be approximated via gradient outer products. A sharp transition from dense to block-diagonal structure should be observable near the point where parameter count exceeds effective data rank. The prediction is robust to whether one uses the empirical Fisher or the true FIM; both should exhibit the qualitative transition.

Prediction 2: Memorization-to-Compression Phase Change.
For a fixed rare signal $x_{\text{rare}}$ governed by a generative grammar $G$, small models (below the decoupling threshold) will exhibit pure memorization: they can reproduce $x_{\text{rare}}$ verbatim but fail on held-out samples from $G$. Large models (above the threshold) will exhibit compositional generalization, correctly answering novel queries that require applying $G$. Crucially, our theory predicts that this transition correlates specifically with the FIM sparsity transition from Prediction 1, not merely with raw parameter count. This distinguishes our claim from generic "emergent ability" narratives.

Prediction 3: Alignment Damage Curve.
Measuring the projection norm $\|\mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{M}_G} \theta\|$ as a function of alignment steps (e.g., RLHF or instruction tuning) should reveal one of two regimes. If conditions (A3–A5) hold (i.e., alignment gradients are approximately orthogonal to $\mathcal{M}_G$), the norm should plateau at a non-zero value, indicating stability. If alignment gradients have significant projection onto $\mathcal{M}_G$, the norm should decay toward zero, indicating subspace collapse. A plot of $\|\mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{M}_G} \theta(t)\|^2$ vs. RLHF step $t$ will directly test the Lyapunov stability argument of Theorem 10.1.

Prediction 4: Recombination Validity.
For any pair of decoupled grammars $G_1, G_2$ identified via FIM block structure, the model should be able to generate coherent, logically consistent outputs for the combined concept $G_1 \wedge G_2$, even when zero training examples of the combination exist. Logical consistency can be evaluated by human experts or automated theorem provers (for formal domains). In contrast, models below the decoupling threshold should produce incoherent or contradictory outputs for the same prompts. This prediction operationalizes Proposition 6.1.

Practical Takeaways for Practitioners.

· Monitor FIM sparsity across model scales to verify the decoupling transition.
· Track projection norms of known knowledge subspaces during RLHF to detect alignment damage early.
· Consider projection-corrected updates as a lightweight safety mechanism to preserve valuable latent structures during fine-tuning.

These predictions are amenable to empirical investigation using open-source models across a range of scales, synthetic data with known generative grammars, and controlled post-training interventions. Confirmation of these predictions would provide strong evidence for the geometric theory; falsification would indicate the need for alternative explanatory frameworks.

